  "prompt": "Which Ivy League university is the easiest to get into?",
  "response": "It's tricky to definitively say which Ivy League school is the \"easiest\" to get into, as \"easy\" is relative and depends on the applicant. However, based purely on **acceptance rates**, **Cornell University** generally has the highest acceptance rate among the Ivies.\n\nHere's a general idea of recent acceptance rates (keep in mind these fluctuate year to year):\n\n*   **Cornell University:** Typically around 8-9%\n*   Other Ivies (Harvard, Yale, Princeton, Columbia, UPenn, Dartmouth, Brown): Generally range from 3-7%\n\n**Important Considerations Beyond Acceptance Rates:**\n\n*   **Acceptance rates are a very broad statistic.** They don't tell the whole story.\n*   **Different Programs:** Some programs within a university are more competitive than others.  For example, certain engineering or business programs at Cornell might be more competitive than some programs in the humanities.\n*   **Fit:** A school might be a better \"fit\" for you based on your academic interests, extracurricular activities, and personal preferences, even if its acceptance rate is lower. A strong fit can increase your chances of admission, even at a highly selective school.\n*   **Strength of Applicant Pool:** The applicant pools at these universities are incredibly competitive. Even at Cornell, you still need to be an outstanding student with impressive achievements to be considered.\n\n**In summary:**\n\nWhile Cornell often has the highest acceptance rate of the Ivies, remember that *all* Ivy League schools are extremely selective. Focus on developing a strong academic record, pursuing your passions, and crafting a compelling application that showcases your unique strengths and goals. Don't just target the school with the \"easiest\" acceptance rate; aim for the school that is the best *fit* for you.\n",
